k Geographies of the Selva -- t12 Geographies of Ghettoization: Absences, Presences, and Boundaries -- t13 Spaces of Engagement and the Geographies of Obligation: Responses to the Holocaust -- t14 Hello Darkness: Envoi and Caveat -- tSection 4 Microgeographies of Memory, Witnessing, and Representation -- t15 Th e Interruption of Witnessing: Relations of Distance and Proximity in Claude Lanzmann’s Shoah -- t16 A Mobile Holocaust? Rethinking Testimony with Cultural Geography -- t17 What Remains? Sites of Deportation in Contemporary European Daily Life: Th e Case of Drancy -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributor Biographies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLebensraum: the entitlement of “legitimate” Germans to living space. Entfernung: the expulsion of “undesirables” to create empty space for German resettlement. During his thirteen years leading Germany, Hitler developed and made use of a number of powerful geostrategical concepts such as these in order to justify his imperialist expansion, exploitation, and genocide. As his twisted manifestation of spatial theory grew in Nazi ideology, it created a new and violent relationship between people and space in Germany and beyond. With Hitler’s Geographies, editors Paolo Giaccaria and Claudio Minca examine the variety of ways in which spatial theory evolved and was translated into real-world action under the Third Reich. They have gathered an outstanding collection by leading scholars, presenting key concepts and figures as well exploring the undeniable link between biopolitical power and spatial expansion and exclusion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGeographyxPolitical aspects. 0aNational socialism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ahistorical geography, political history, politic